{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_18","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,260p' .workflow/iphone-app-factory/research/app-store.md\"","aggregated_output":"# WakeTask App Store Research (US iPhone alarm accountability segment)\n\n## Scope and limitations\n- Requested inputs `.workflow/iphone-app-factory/context.md` and `quality-bar.json` were not present in this workspace at research time.\n- `APIFY_TOKEN` presence check returned `true`, but no ready-to-run `iphone-app-factory` App Store review scraper was found in this repo, so this report uses live App Store listing/review excerpts and related market signals rather than a full exported review dataset.\n- Evidence quality for this report: `partial`.\n\n## Candidate apps and relevance\n1. [Alarmy: Loud Alarm Clock,Sleep App](https://apps.apple.com/us/app/alarmy-alarm-clock-sleep/id1163786766)\n- Relevance: category leader in high-friction wakeups (missions, loud alarms, habit framing), broad US penetration, benchmark for feature breadth.\n\n2. [Nuj Alarm Clock App](https://apps.apple.com/us/app/nuj-alarm-clock/id1557053396)\n- Relevance: commitment-stakes model (monetary loss/charity) directly maps to “high-friction accountability.”\n\n3. [Challenges Alarm Clock App](https://apps.apple.com/us/app/challenges-alarm-clock/id1247289889)\n- Relevance: pure challenge-based dismissal (math/maze/shake/remember/step), direct competitor for mission-driven wake reliability.\n\n4. [Barcode Alarm Clock](https://apps.apple.com/us/app/barcode-alarm-clock/id699437630)\n- Relevance: classic “scan an object in another room” mechanic; validated physical-displacement pattern for heavy sleepers.\n\n5. [Get Up - Challenge Alarm Clock](https://apps.apple.com/us/app/get-up-challenge-alarm-clock/id1620790645)\n- Relevance: combines movement, cognitive tasks, streaks, and Apple Health integration; closer to behavior-change product than simple utility.\n\n6. [Mathe Alarm Clock - Math Alarm](https://apps.apple.com/us/app/mathe-alarm-clock-math-alarm/id823532916)\n- Relevance: focused cognitive-friction alarm with substantial ratings footprint, useful for UX and retention benchmark.\n\n7. [Orlo Alarm: Wake Up Challenge](https://apps.apple.com/us/app/orlo-alarm-wake-up-challenge/id6760335025)\n- Relevance: newer mission-based entrant with identity/account sync and routine framing; signal of ongoing market entry.\n\n8. [WalkUp Alarm](https://apps.apple.com/us/app/walkup-alarm/id6759010890)\n- Relevance: movement-only dismissal (step count) with simple value prop; tests whether narrower “one strong mechanic” can compete.\n\n## Recent review/listing themes\n\n### Recurring complaints\n- Reliability anxiety remains core: users in this category explicitly fear bypassing/cheating alarms (power-off, silence paths, accidental dismiss behavior).\n- Friction overreach: some users report challenge burden when managing future alarms (setup fatigue, too many forced tasks).\n- Monetization friction: subscription gating and perceived paywalls are repeatedly called out in mission-alarm listings.\n- Edge-case frustration: challenge apps can create lockout-like moments (too hard/too long challenge when user is time-constrained).\n\n### Frequent feature requests\n- Better anti-cheat controls without making every morning punitive.\n- Smarter fallback paths (e.g., emergency dismiss, graded difficulty, time-window-sensitive challenge length).\n- More customization per alarm: challenge type, difficulty, snooze policy, and context-aware modes for workdays vs weekends.\n- Better cross-device/session continuity and wake history analytics.\n\n### Delight moments users highlight\n- Physical displacement mechanics (barcode/steps/photo) are repeatedly praised as actually effective for heavy sleepers.\n- Commitment stakes (e.g., Nuj) are seen as uniquely effective because they add real consequence.\n- “No snooze/no easy stop” positioning resonates strongly with users who self-identify as chronic snoozers.\n\n## Fast-growing vs merely large\n\n### Appears merely large (incumbent scale)\n- Alarmy and long-standing challenge/math apps show large installed bases and ratings volume, indicating mature demand and strong category awareness.\n- These products are broad platforms (sleep sounds, trackers, routines, widgets), not just alarm mechanics.\n\n### Appears fast-growing (new entrant velocity signals)\n- New 2024-2026 challenge apps (Orlo, WalkUp, Unsnooze, WakeNow, newer math/challenge variants) suggest active entry and experimentation around narrow accountability mechanics.\n- Growth appears mechanic-led rather than brand-led: apps compete on one memorable forcing function (speech, steps, scan, mission bundles).\n- iOS alarm-surface changes and third-party AlarmKit improvements are likely lowering reliability barriers for third-party alarm apps, potentially accelerating challenger adoption.\n\n## Concrete product opportunities for WakeTask\n1. Adaptive friction engine\n- Start with user-selected baseline (light/medium/hard), then auto-adjust challenge difficulty using recent snooze/failure behavior so accountability rises only when needed.\n\n2. “Two-layer trust” reliability design\n- Layer 1: hard-to-dismiss wake challenge.\n- Layer 2: fail-safe escalation (backup alarm pattern + secondary channel) when challenge completion risk is detected.\n\n3. Consequence wallet without pure punishment\n- Offer stake options beyond cash loss: social accountability check-in, streak protection deposits, or pre-committed morning task unlocks.\n\n4. Time-critical mode\n- On high-urgency mornings, shorten challenge path while preserving anti-cheat guarantees (e.g., one strong proof instead of multi-step gauntlet).\n\n5. Proof-of-awake score\n- Daily score combining movement, response latency, and challenge quality; trendline becomes habit product moat and supports coaching.\n\n6. Anti-cheat transparency\n- Explicitly explain what counts as cheating and why; give users a transparent audit log when alarms are missed/dismissed to reduce trust anxiety.\n\n7. Segment-specific wake recipes\n- Ready-made templates: students, shift workers, ADHD/chronic snoozers, parents; each template tunes challenge type, escalation, and timing.\n\n## Evidence quality\n- Overall: `partial`\n- Why: live App Store pages and current market signals were used, but no full live Apify export of review corpora was executed from this repo workflow.\n- Recommendation to upgrade to `live`: run a dedicated App Store review scrape (last 90 days) per candidate, then cluster complaints/requests quantitatively.\n\n## Sources\n- https://apps.apple.com/us/app/alarmy-alarm-clock-sleep/id1163786766\n- https://apps.apple.com/us/app/nuj-alarm-clock/id1557053396\n- https://apps.apple.com/us/app/challenges-alarm-clock/id1247289889\n- https://apps.apple.com/us/app/barcode-alarm-clock/id699437630\n- https://apps.apple.com/us/app/get-up-challenge-alarm-clock/id1620790645\n- https://apps.apple.com/us/app/mathe-alarm-clock-math-alarm/id823532916\n- https://apps.apple.com/us/app/orlo-alarm-wake-up-challenge/id6760335025\n- https://apps.apple.com/us/app/walkup-alarm/id6759010890\n- https://www.macrumors.com/2025/06/11/ios-26-third-party-alarm-apps/\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
